          "type": "assistant",
          "text": "I now have a thorough understanding of the system. Let me synthesize the design options and present a plan.\n\nHere's my analysis of the problem and options:\n\n---\n\n## Understanding the Current System\n\nRight now, conversations only enter the system when a Cursor `postToolUse` hook fires — meaning **a file must have been edited**. Passive (planning/research) conversations never trigger any hook at all. The `update_prompts_to_latest` step at post-commit only refreshes conversations already tracked in the working log.\n\n**To your question — yes, we have the previous commit timestamp.** The `parent_sha` is always available at post-commit time, and `git log -1 --format=%ct <parent_sha>` gives its Unix timestamp. That's a natural bootstrap for a time-based scan.\n\n---\n\n## The Core Challenge\n\nThe Cursor DB doesn't expose a \"list all conversations after timestamp T\" API. Conversations live as `composerData:<uuid>` key-value rows in `cursorDiskKV`. To enumerate new ones you'd do:\n\n```sql\nSELECT key FROM cursorDiskKV WHERE key LIKE 'composerData:%'\n```\n\n...and then check each unknown UUID's last bubble `createdAt` to see if it falls in the right time window.\n\n---\n\n## Options\n\n**Option A: Watermark + scan at post-commit (your idea, refined)**\n\nStore a `last_chat_scan_at` watermark in the internal DB (the existing `git-ai` SQLite). At post-commit:\n1. Load the watermark (default: previous commit's Unix timestamp, from `git log -1 --format=%ct <parent_sha>`)\n2. Query all `composerData:*` UUIDs from Cursor DB\n3. Filter out UUIDs already in `internal_db.prompts.external_thread_id`\n4. For each new UUID, check only the last bubble's `createdAt` — if it's > watermark, fetch and record the full transcript\n5. Store these as context-only records (no `total_additions`/`total_deletions`), tagged in the git note as `context_conversations`\n6. Write `last_chat_scan_at = now` back to the internal DB\n\n**Pros:** Automatic, no extra hooks, leverages what already exists  \n**Cons:** Requires scanning all `composerData:*` keys at commit time (a local SQLite scan, so fast in practice)\n\n**Option B: Daemon-based polling (background)**\n\nHave the git-ai daemon periodically poll the Cursor DB for new conversation IDs and record them in a staging table in the internal DB. At post-commit, drain the staging table into the git note.\n\n**Pros:** Zero overhead at commit time; near-real-time capture even without commits  \n**Cons:** Daemon dependency; more moving parts; daemon currently doesn't have this responsibility\n\n**Option C: New lightweight hook (exploration only)**\n\nAdd a third Cursor hook (e.g. `onConversationEnd` or `agentStop`) that fires when the user closes/finishes a conversation without making edits, and calls `git-ai checkpoint cursor` with no `file_path`.\n\n**Pros:** Only processes conversations as they happen; no scan needed  \n**Cons:** Cursor currently only exposes `preToolUse`/`postToolUse` — this would require Cursor to add a new hook type, which we can't control\n\n---\n\n## Recommendation\n\n**Option A** is the cleanest path with the least new infrastructure. The scan is lightweight (local SQLite, ~milliseconds), it composes naturally with the existing post-commit flow, and the watermark sidesteps the \"which commits did I already see?\" problem cleanly.\n\nKey design decisions to confirm before building:\n\n1. **Where to store the watermark** — a new `settings` table in the existing internal DB (`git-ai.sqlite`) is the most natural fit\n2. **How to represent these in the git note** — a new top-level `\"context_conversations\"` key in the JSON section, parallel to `\"prompts\"`, vs. unifying them under `\"prompts\"` with a `\"kind\": \"context_only\"` field\n3. **Scope** — should context conversations be per-repo (only include conversations that referenced files in this workspace) or all conversations from the time window?",
